<div class="modal fade" id="MODAL_ALERT" data-bs-backdrop="static" data-bs-keyboard="false">
    <div class="modal-dialog modal-lg modal-dialog-scrollable" role="document" id="MODAL_SHARE">
        <div class="modal-content">
            <div class="modal-header">
                <h5 class="modal-title" id="MODAL_ALERT_TITLE">Share Agreement</h5>
                <a href="#" class="close" data-bs-dismiss="modal">
                    <em class="icon ni ni-cross-sm"></em>
                </a>
            </div>
            <div class="modal-body modal-body-md">
                <h6>Publish to Internal (Organization):</h6>
                <p>Publishing to internal users within an organization is a secure and controlled way to share Power BI content. This method is ideal for collaborating on business intelligence insights among team members, departments, or any internal stakeholders. Key features include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Secure Access:</b> Access is restricted to users within the organization, ensuring that sensitive data is only accessible to authorized personnel.</li>
                    <li><b>Integration with Azure Active Directory:</b> Users can leverage Azure Active Directory (AAD) for seamless access management and authentication.</li>
                    <li><b>Granular Permissions:</b> Fine-grained control over permissions allows content creators to define who can view or edit specific reports and dashboards.</li>
                </ul>
                <br />
                <h6>Publish to Web External (Customer):</h6>
                <p>Publishing to web external is designed for sharing Power BI content with individuals outside the organization, such as customers, partners, or vendors. This option offers a more open and accessible approach, but considerations include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Public Access:</b> Reports and dashboards published to the web are publicly accessible via a unique URL.</li>
                    <li><b>Limited Security:</b> While convenient for external sharing, it's crucial to avoid including sensitive or confidential information.</li>
                    <li><b>No Authentication Required:</b> External users do not need a Power BI account for access, simplifying the process but requiring careful consideration of shared information.</li>
                </ul>
                <br />
                <b>Considerations and Limitations:</b>
                <ul>
                    <li>- Reports using row-level security.</li>
                    <li>- Reports connecting to data using DirectQuery. Connect using composite or import mode instead. Read about the differences between the modes.</li>
                    <li>- Reports using any Live Connection data source.</li>
                    <li>- Reports using a shared semantic model that is stored in a different workspace from the report.</li>
                    <li>- Shared and certified semantic models.</li>
                    <li>- Reports shared to you directly or through an app.</li>
                    <li>- Reports in a workspace in which you aren't an edit member.</li>
                    <li>- "R" and Python visuals aren't currently supported in Publish to web reports.</li>
                    <li>- Exporting data from visuals in a report that has been published to the web.</li>
                    <li>- Q&A for Power BI visuals.</li>
                    <li>- Reports containing report-level DAX measures.</li>
                    <li>- Single sign-on data query models, including composite models on Power BI semantic models or Azure Analysis Services.</li>
                    <li>- Secure confidential or proprietary information.</li>
                    <li>- The automatic authentication capability provided with the Embed option doesn't work with the Power BI JavaScript API. For the Power BI JavaScript API, use the user owns data approach to embedding.</li>
                    <li>- Admins can block public internet access, as described in Private links for accessing Power BI. In that case, the Publish to Web option is grayed out for your tenant in the Power BI admin portal.</li>
                    <li>- License enforcement for custom visuals.</li>
                    <li>- Uncertified visuals from the organizational store, when the global tenant switch of the organization for uncertified visuals is on.</li>
                    <li>- Public visuals from the organizational store, when the global tenant switch of the organization doesn't allow visuals created using the Power BI SDK.</li>
                    <li>- The user who created the embed code needs to maintain access to the report for the embed code to work. This includes requiring a Pro or Premium Per User license as required by the workspace.</li>
                    <li>- Paginated reports.</li>
                    <li>- Multiple-language reports.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>In summary, Power BI offers flexibility in sharing insights. Publishing to internal users provides a secure environment for collaboration within the organization, while publishing to the web external is a convenient way to share insights with a broader audience.</p>

            </div>
            <div class="modal-footer">
                <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" onclick="AGREE_ALERT()">I'm agree with this.</button>
